%I A391110 #28 Apr 30 2026 00:28:57
%S A391110 1,1,2,4,4,8,4,12,8,16,8,8,16,12,28,16,16,16,36,16,40,32,48,20,24,52,
%T A391110 28,60,32,48,32,32,72,36,32,72,40,64,88,32,96,48,32,100,48,52,108,112,
%U A391110 56,96,120,60,100,64,48,64,136,64,112,72,72,148,128,156,64,72,80,144,64,172
%N A391110 Number of elements in a reduced system of residues modulo x + y*i, i = sqrt(-1), for integers x and y as defined in the comments.
%C A391110 Let phi_i : Z[i] -> Z be the generalization of the Euler totient function to the Gaussian integers, defined as phi_i(z) = Product_{p^e|z} (N(p) - 1) * N(p^(e-1)), where p is a Gaussian prime and N(p) is the norm of p. Then a(n) = phi_i(x + y*i) for x and y such that x^2 + y^2 = A001481(n), x <= y, and y - x > s - r for all other integers r <= s such that r^2 + s^2 = A001481(n). Note that phi_i(x +/- y*i) = phi_i(y +/- x*i). - _Miles Englezou_, Apr 24 2026
%C A391110 For Gaussian integers alpha = x + y*i = A229140(n) + A385236(n)*i the totient phi_i(alpha), the order of the multiplicative group of quadratic integers Z[i] modulo alpha, is computed by factoring norm N_alpha = x^2 + y^2 = A001481(n) into rational primes and multiplying together
%C A391110 (1) for ramified prime 2: order phi_i(2^k) = 2^(k-1),
%C A391110 (2) inert primes p = 4*n + 3: phi_i(p^k) = p^(2*k) - p^(2*k-2),
%C A391110 (3) split primes q = 4*n + 1: phi_i(q^k) = q^k - q^(k-1),
%C A391110 with k the multiplicity of each prime element in alpha. That is, apply the group structure for irreducible elements in quadratic ring Z[i] as summarized in Lassak and Porubsky, p. 277-279. The rational and quadratic totients then differ for 20 of the 87 Gaussian integers A229140(n) + A385236(n)*i.
%H A391110 Miles Englezou, <a href="/A391110/b391110.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 2..10001</a>
%H A391110 James T. Cross, <a href="https://doi.org/10.2307/2322785">The Euler phi-function in the Gaussian integers</a>, American Mathematical Monthly, Vol. 90, Issue 8 (1983), pp. 518-528.
%H A391110 Miroslav Lassak and Stefan Porubsky, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1006/jnth.1996.0123">Fermat-Euler theorem in algebraic number fields</a>, Journal of Number Theory, Vol. 60 (1996), Issue 2.
%F A391110 a(n) = phi_i(A229140(n) + A385236(n)*i), for phi_i as defined in the Englezou comment.
%e A391110 a(64) = 128, since A229140(64) + A385236(64)*i = 3 + 12*i with norm 153, which in Z[i] factors as 3*(1 + 4*i), giving totient 8 * 16.
%e A391110 a(97) = 80 since A001481(97) = 250 = 5^2 + 15^2 = 9^2 + 13^2, 15 - 5 > 13 - 9, and therefore phi_i(5 + 15*i) = 80 = a(97). Note that phi_i(9 + 13*i) = 100.
%e A391110 a(216) = 400 since A001481(216) = 625 = 0^2 + 25^2 = 7^2 + 24^2 = 15^2 + 20^2, 25 - 0 > 24 - 7 > 20 - 15, and therefore phi_i(0 + 25*i) = 400 = a(216). Note that phi_i(7 + 24*i) = 500 and phi_i(15 + 20*i) = 400.
%o A391110 (PARI) lst(lim) = my(Qi = bnfinit(t^2+1), A = []); for(n=1, oo, if(#A >= lim, break); my(f = bnfisintnorm(Qi, n)); if(f, my(a=-1,b); until(issquare(n-a*a,&b),a++); A = concat(A, idealstar(Qi,[a,b]~,0)[1]))); A
%Y A391110 The least x such that norm x^2 + y^2 = A001481: A229140, with corresponding b-values A385236.
%Y A391110 Euler's totient function on rational integers: A000010.
%Y A391110 Carmichael's lambda function on Gaussian integers: A391111.
%Y A391110 An alternative totient function on Gaussian integers: A103224.
%K A391110 nonn,easy,changed
%O A391110 2,3
%A A391110 _Sjoerd J. Schaper_, Nov 29 2025
%E A391110 Name clarified, offset changed, comments edited, and examples added by _Miles Englezou_, Apr 24 2026
